<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="70" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
<typeStatus>Type</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Brasilien”">
&quot;
<collectingCountry name="Brazil">Brasilien</collectingCountry>
&quot;
</normalizedToken>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Sellow s.n.</emphasis>
(&quot;in herb. Berol.&quot;) (
<typeStatus>holotype</typeStatus>
: B! [B10 0242234]).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="70">
<bibRefCitation author="Nilsson, LA" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" refId="B12" refString="Nilsson, LA, 1892. Studien über die Xyrideen. Kongl. Svenska Vetenskapsakad. Handl.24(14): 1-75." title="Studien u ̈ ber die Xyrideen. Kongl. Svenska Vetenskapsakad. Handl. 24 (14): 1 - 75." year="1892">Nilsson (1892)</bibRefCitation>
cited the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Sellow s.n.</emphasis>
collection in the protologue as at the Berlin herbarium (B). 
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, LB" editor="Hoehne, FC" journalOrPublisher="Sao Paulo, fasc. 12, v. 9, n. 2" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" pagination="1 - 214" refId="B16" refString="Smith, LB, Downs, RJ, 1968. Xyridaceae. In: Hoehne, FC, Teixeira, AR, Eds., Flora Brasilica. Sao Paulo, fasc. 12, v. 9, n. 2: 1 - 214" title="Xyridaceae." volumeTitle="Flora Brasilica." year="1968">Smith and Downs (1968)</bibRefCitation>
indicated the B sheet as the type, but without specifying the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="type’s">type's</normalizedToken>
category. Considering that only this sheet of this collection is known at B (B10 0242234) and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Nilsson’s">Nilsson's</normalizedToken>
citation of B in the protologue, we can confirm that it is the 
<typeStatus>holotype</typeStatus>
. Although no mention was made in the protologue of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sellow’s">Sellow's</normalizedToken>
collecting number, the label states that it is 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="70">Sellow 1087</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus>holotype</typeStatus>
is a poor specimen, consisting of only one plant with two incomplete spikes, together with added fragments of the inflorescence, but nevertheless corresponds to the characteristics of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
